Democracy without civic connection
Something is owed to democracy in the sense that the government is elected by the people, everywhere in the world.
People have somehow lost faith in elections.
Voter turnout is declining in many countries; in the case of European Parliament elections, voter turnout was so laughably low that the legitimacy of the election result is questionable.
Aside from voter turnout, we have become accustomed to accepting parties or candidates who receive 25% of the cast votes as "winners".
From Holland to Finland and from Argentina to Japan, majority governments are formed based on minorities.
Even the apparent exceptions do not prove the opposite.
Only a few American presidents were elected by more than 10% of the eligible voters. In fact, half of the eligible voters in the US did not even register to vote; of those who did register, half did not vote; and of those who did vote, less than half voted for the election winner.
Even Tony Blair's "landslide" majority in the UK's House of Commons is shaky: The Labour Party received only slightly more than 40% of the votes in the last election in 2002, and this was with a voter turnout of 60%.
Thus, only 24% of the total electorate supported Blair's party.
In most countries, elections look significantly different now than they did twenty or even fifty years ago.
What has happened?
One possible answer is that voters distrust political parties.
Election democracy functions in most countries due to the mediation of organizations that put forward candidates who advocate for specific packages of political possibilities, for a "manifesto" or an "election program."
This long-established practice is no longer functioning for a number of reasons.
Ideological party programs have lost their power; voters no longer accept the packages imposed by the parties, they want to choose and select for themselves.
Political parties have also become machines composed of tightly organized cadres of insiders.
The paradox here is that the parties have become even more clique-like with the loss of their specific ideological orientation.
It is more important for them to belong than to share their specific beliefs.
Such developments have alienated the parties from the voter.
Because most people do not want to belong to a particular party, only a minority plays the party game.
This increases the public's distrust of political parties, and it is also partly because, just like professional sports, it is expensive to participate.
When the costs are borne by the taxpayer, it is seen as bad.
However, without state financial support, parties would have to obtain money through channels that are often dubious, if not even illegal.
Many of the major political scandals of the past few decades began with the financing of parties and their candidates.
Other indications, such as the clear decline in membership, confirm that parties have become unpopular.
Yet, parties are indispensable for a democratic election.
The result is an obvious separation between the visible political actors and the electorate.
Because parties are active in parliaments, the effects of this separation affect one of the most crucial institutions of democracy.
People no longer believe that parliaments represent them and thus endow them with the necessary legitimacy to make decisions on their behalf.
At this point, a second, quite independent development comes into play.
People are more impatient today than ever before.
As consumers, they are accustomed to immediate satisfaction.
However, as voters, they have to wait before they feel the results of the election, which they cast their ballots for.
Sometimes they never see the desired results.
Democracy needs time not only for elections but also for deliberations and thoughtful consideration.
The consumer as a voter, however, does not accept this and therefore turns away.
There are alternatives. Yet, each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
"Direct Action" through demonstrations has become a regular and often effective event.
For less mobile people, it could be replaced by the possibility of expressing opinions electronically; this ranges from internet chat rooms to electronic messages to political leaders.
Then there are the non-governmental organizations. They often have undemocratic structures, but seem to be more closely connected to citizens.
Furthermore, there is, of course, the possibility of completely disengaging and leaving politics to the experts, in order to focus on other aspects of life.
This likely poses the greatest risks, as it promotes the creeping authoritarianism that is a sign of our times.
However, the other signs of the separation between politics and citizens also create a rather unstable state, as no one can say anymore how representative the prevailing views are.
Some want to cut through the knot with more direct democracy.
But a lasting connection between leaders and followers cannot be established by reducing public discussion to simple voting alternatives.
There are even more reasons to hold onto the classical institutions of parliamentary democracy and try to reconnect them with the citizenry.
After all, unpopular parties and declining voter turnout might prove to be a temporary phenomenon.
New parties could emerge and breathe life into elections and representative governments again.
However, this might not be enough to restore the general legitimacy that elected governments have lost.
Therefore, the first concern for all those who value freedom in the constitution should be to rethink democracy and its institutions.
